description:
The major part of the thermal energy supply of the contemporary society is based on combustion of fossil fuels. "Flames" or combustion is utilized in a variety of engineering fields. This course aims at deeper understanding of combustion phenomena.
This course will consist of the following topics:
1) Chemical kinetics (rate of chemical reactions);
2) Reaction mechanisms;
3) Premixed Flames;
4) Nonpremixed Flames;
5) Ignition Processes;
6) Low-Temperature Oxidation.

Electrochemistry is the field that thermodynamically or kinetically investigates electron transfer reactions at the electrode/electrolyte interface. In recent years, knowledge of electrochemistry is required for the development of devices such as batteries and industrial technology such as water electrolysis, so electrochemistry is an indispensable fundamental study for advanced technology development. With this in mind, the objective of this course is as follows;
1.Students can explain the basic theory of electrochemistry and the principles of basic/advanced electrochemical measurement techniques required in research and development related to electrochemistry and analyze the data obtained by various electrochemical measurements.
2.Students can explain the contents of English academic papers on cutting-edge electrochemistry-related topics.
